# Booking Integrations

## Canonical model

`msg-data_model/` is the source of truth for the booking integration schema.
Read `msg-data_model/ddl.sql` before creating or modifying migrations.
Read `msg-data_model/platform_mappings.md` before mapping provider data.

## Architecture rules

- `suppliers` and `experiences` are the root entities. NEVER create parallel tables.
- One supplier = one booking system. `suppliers.booking_system` holds the provider name. `suppliers.booking_system_data` jsonb holds credentials/config.
- Only create a table when the entity needs independent querying. Sub-entities (unit types, extras, participants, answers, documents, payments) live as jsonb columns on their parent.
- Holds are bookings with `status = 'on_hold'` — no separate table.
- Contact info (booker) lives directly on `booking` — no separate customer table.

## Tables (7 new + 1 ALTER)

1. ALTER `suppliers` — add `booking_system text`
2. `experience_option` — with `unit_types`, `extras`, `custom_fields` jsonb
3. `availability_slot` — with `unit_prices` jsonb
4. `booking` — with `participants`, `answers`, `documents`, `payments` jsonb
5. `booking_line` — with `units`, `extras` jsonb
6. `external_ref` — provider ID ↔ canonical ID
7. `webhook_event` — with inline projection columns
8. `sync_cursor` — incremental import state

## Column conventions

- Use `text` for all status columns (no PostgreSQL enums). Valid values documented in `platform_mappings.md`.
- Every table that imports provider data MUST have `raw_data jsonb` with the original payload.
- Every webhook event MUST store `payload jsonb` — immutable after insert.
- jsonb array columns (`unit_types`, `participants`, etc.) use documented schemas — see examples in `ddl.sql`.

